Toolbox Demo: Samoa

1 Introduction

The Ocean Health Index (OHI) framework measures the health of coupled human-ocean ecosystems in different contexts by accommodating differences in local environmental characteristics, cultural priorities, and information availability and quality. The OHI framework assesses a suite of benefits the ocean provides humans - called goals - using the best information available. It distills complex socio-ecological relationships and context-specific targets into scores that can be repeated so that management can track and respond through time.

Assessments using the OHI framework results in scores for each goal as well as in a single score for overall ocean health, which is a weighted-average of each goals score. Each goals score is calculated compared to a target called a reference point, and thus the score represents how close the goal is to meeting that target, on a scale from 0-100. Scores can be represented on a flower plot, where the center value is the overall OHI score. Each petal of the flower plot represents a goal; the length is the score of that particular goal and the width is its weight: contribution to the overall score.

2 Overview

To get some hands-on experience with the Toolbox, we will explore how Ocean Health Index (OHI) scores respond when you change the following:

  1. remove the NP goal

You will be using the OHI Toolbox software to do this, and follow the instructions here (workshop-toolbox.Rmd). Walk through line-by-line and execute the code in R; the order does matter so be sure to proceed line-by-line.

Your final figures will be saved as .pngs within the sam folder you downloaded: sam/toolbox-demo/reports/figures.

2.1 Get the sam repository

Well be playing with the Toolbox for the global OHI assessments; we calculate scores each year for 220 coastal nations and territories. We have copied this into a GitHub repository called sam for Samoa. Lets get it on your computer.

  1. Go to github.com/OHI-Science/sam. This is the sam repository (called repo).
  2. Click on the green clone or download button.
  3. Clone or download somewhere you can find on your computer. If you are familiar with GitHub, clone this repository. Otherwise click Download ZIP.
  4. Navigate to where you saved the sam repo on your computer and double-click the sam.Rproj file. This will open RStudio (which is how you should always interface with R).
  5. Within the RStudio file directory pane (bottom right), navigate to the toolbox-demo folder. Inside is a mix of .R scripts and .csv files. We will just focus on a few of them.

2.2 Setup

Since were in RStudio with a .Rproj file, our current working directory is wherever/you/saved/it/sam. All of our work in the Toolbox happens in the toolbox-demo folder within the sam folder. (Even these instructions are within the toolbox-demo folder!) But we need to let R know that we want to be inside the toolbox-demo folder. Lets change the working directory to the toolbox-demo folder, and install the packages we need to get going.

Troubleshooting: If you have any problems, check that R and RStudio are up-to-date. If needed, update R here and RStudio here.

Run the following code:

## set working directory to sam/toolbox-demo with setwd()

2.3 Calculate scores

We can calculate OHI scores by sourcing calculate_scores.r (below). This uses the following files, which are all in our current working directory, sam/toolbox-demo:

  • input data layers in the layers folder
  • goal models and reference points in conf/functions.r
  • goal weights in conf/goals.csv
  • calculated scores for all goals and all 220 regions are saved in scores.csv.

Note: because the Toolbox relies on these file names for calculation and for visualizing, well be overwriting some of these files (after saving the originals) to use in each of the steps as we go forward.

## Before we do anything, let's save copies of original files
file.copy('scores.csv','scores_orig.csv', overwrite = TRUE)
## [1] TRUE
file.copy('conf/goals.csv',   'conf/goals_orig.csv', overwrite = TRUE)
## [1] TRUE
file.copy('conf/functions.r', 'conf/functions_orig.r', overwrite = TRUE)
## [1] TRUE
file.copy('conf/pressures_matrix.csv', 'conf/pressures_matrix_orig.csv', overwrite = TRUE)
## [1] TRUE
file.copy('conf/resilience_matrix.csv', 'conf/resilience_matrix_orig.csv', overwrite = TRUE)
## [1] TRUE
## Calculate scores. The Toolbox will describe each step as it checks all the data layers and then calculates the OHI components. It will save all this in scores.csv.
source('calculate_scores.r')

2.4 Visualize OHI scores for Samoa

We just calculated scores for all 220 regions in the global assessment. But now lets just inspect one region, Samoa. Each region has a unique numeric identifier. You can run this to view the full list of regions and find their numeric region identifier called a rgn_id: View(read_csv('layers/rgn_global.csv')). Use use the search bar in the top right of the View pane to find your country and note its rgn_id. (Or, you can trust me that the rgn_id for Samoa is 152.)

Youll assign it in R now as rgn_id_sam:

## assign your rgn_id
rgn_id_sam <-  152 # Samoa

2.5 Flower plot for your region

Now, lets check Samoas flower plot. The plot_flower_local() function will make figures for you, saving them as .pngs in sam/toolbox-demo/reports/figures and displaying them in the RStudio Viewer

Run the following it will save a file with your regions name, for example sam/toolbox-demo/reports/figures/flower_orig/Samoa.png.. The PlotFlower() function will use the scores.csv file that was saved from calculate_scores.R

## now, create a flower plot for Samoa
PlotFlower(region_plot = rgn_id_sam,
           assessment_name = "Samoa",
           dir_fig_save    = "reports/figures/flower_orig")

2.6 Remove a Goal

Now lets remove a goal that might not represent Samoa: Natural Products.

## assign goal to remove
goal_remove <- "NP" # the 2- or 3- letter code must be in quotes. 

## remove the goal that we want to exclude and save in the goals.csv file 
read.csv("conf/goals_orig.csv") %>%
  filter(goal != goal_remove) %>%
  write.csv('conf/goals.csv', na='', row.names = FALSE) 

## also from the pressures_matrix file 
read.csv("conf/pressures_matrix_orig.csv") %>%
  filter(goal != goal_remove) %>%
  write.csv('conf/pressures_matrix.csv', na='', row.names = FALSE) 

## also from the resilience_matrix file 
read.csv("conf/resilience_matrix_orig.csv") %>%
  filter(goal != goal_remove) %>%
  write.csv('conf/resilience_matrix.csv', na='', row.names = FALSE)
